//Maximum Subarray
//Given an integer array nums, find the subarray with the largest sum, and return its sum.
//Example 1:
//Input: nums = [-2,1,-3,4,-1,2,1,-5,4]
//Output: 6
//Explanation: The subarray [4,-1,2,1] has the largest sum 6.
//Example 2:
//Input: nums = [1]
//Output: 1
//Explanation: The subarray [1] has the largest sum 1.
//Example 3:
//Input: nums = [5,4,-1,7,8]
//Output: 23
//Explanation: The subarray [5,4,-1,7,8] has the largest sum 23.

Brute Force Approach ->
Compare every possible subarray and keep track of the maximum sum found.

class Solution {
public:
    int maxSubArray(vector<int>& nums) {
        int maxSum = nums[0];
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {
            int currentSum = 0;
            for(int j = i; j < nums.size(); j++) {
                currentSum += nums[j];
                maxSum = max(maxSum, currentSum);
            }
        }
        return maxSum;
    }
};

Intuition ->
Generate every possible subarray.
Calculate its sum.
Keep updating the maximum sum encountered.

Complexity Analysis ->

Time Complexity -> O(n²)
where:
n = size of nums
Reason:
For every starting index, we expand the subarray to every possible ending index.

Space Complexity -> O(1)
Reason:
Only a few variables are used.

Optimal Approach -> (Kadane's Algorithm)

class Solution {
public:
    int maxSubArray(vector<int>& nums) {
        int currentSum = nums[0];
        int maxSum = nums[0];

        for(int i = 1; i < nums.size(); i++) {
            currentSum = max(nums[i], currentSum + nums[i]);                       //currentSum would discard stuff immediately if it is smaller than current element because all of that would just be extra baggage.
            maxSum = max(maxSum, currentSum);                                     //Out of all best-ending-here subarrays I've seen so far, which one is globally the best?
        }
        return maxSum;
    }
};

Intuition ->
At every index, we have two choices:
Start a new subarray from the current element.
Extend the previous subarray.
Choose whichever gives a larger sum.
Keep track of the best sum seen so far.

Complexity Analysis ->

Time Complexity -> O(n)
where:
n = size of nums
Reason:
We traverse the array only once.

Space Complexity -> O(1)
Reason:
Only a few variables are used regardless of input size.

